### Description

If I declare a class component in a types.d.ts to distribute in a library like so:

```typescript
export declare class MyExampleComponent {
    propName1: boolean;
    propName2: string;
    propName3: number;
    static Éµfac: Éµngcc0.ÉµÉµFactoryDeclaration<MyExampleComponent, never>;
    static Éµcmp: Éµngcc0.ÉµÉµComponentDeclaration<MyExampleComponent, "my-example", never, { "propName1": "propName1"; "propName2": "propName2"; "propName2": "propName2"; }, {}, never, never, false>;
}
```

I can enable strict type checking within angular templates to make sure that the value passed into `propName1` is a boolean (same for the other props).

However, if I split the type declaration like so:

```typescript
export declare interface MyExampleComponent {
    propName1: boolean;
    propName2: string;
    propName3: number;
}
export declare class MyExampleComponent {
    static Éµfac: Éµngcc0.ÉµÉµFactoryDeclaration<MyExampleComponent, never>;
    static Éµcmp: Éµngcc0.ÉµÉµComponentDeclaration<MyExampleComponent, "my-example", never, { "propName1": "propName1"; "propName2": "propName2"; "propName2": "propName2"; }, {}, never, never, false>;
}
```

Then it stops checking the types of the properties. It can recognize if the prop is misspelled, but it would not give any error if I passed a string into propName1 or anything else like that.

According to typescript rules, the interface's typings should get merged with the class's typings.

